Avoiding unnecessary re‑renders in React is about **controlling when and why components update**. The goal is **not “zero re‑renders”**, but **only re‑render when output actually needs to change**.

Below is a **production‑ready, practical guide** used by experienced React teams.

***

## ✅ First: Understand Why Re‑Renders Happen (Key Mental Model)

A React component re‑renders when **any of these change**:

1.  Its **state**
2.  Its **props**
3.  Its **parent re‑renders**
4.  A **context value it uses changes**

> ✅ Re‑render ≠ DOM update (React diffs first)

***

## ✅ 1. Keep State as Local as Possible (MOST IMPORTANT)

### ❌ Bad (state too high)

```jsx
function App() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState("");

  return (
    <>
      <Input value={value} onChange={setValue} />
      <HeavyList /> {/* re-renders unnecessarily */}
    </>
  );
}
```

### ✅ Good (state moved down)

```jsx
function Input() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState("");
  return <input value={value} onChange={e => setValue(e.target.value)} />;
}
```

✅ Fewer components re-render  
✅ Most powerful optimization

***

## ✅ 2. Use `React.memo` (ONLY When It Helps)

### ✅ When to use

*   Component is expensive
*   Props are stable
*   Parent re-renders often

```jsx
const UserCard = React.memo(function UserCard({ name }) {
  return <div>{name}</div>;
});
```

### ❌ When to avoid

*   Cheap components
*   Props change every render
*   No profiling done

***

## ✅ 3. Stabilize Functions with `useCallback`

### ❌ Causes re-render

```jsx
<Button onClick={() => doSomething()} />
```

### ✅ Stable reference

```jsx
const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  doSomething();
}, []);

<Button onClick={handleClick} />
```

✅ Necessary when passing functions to `memo` components

***

## ✅ 4. Stabilize Objects & Arrays with `useMemo`

### ❌ New object every render

```jsx
<Component config={{ theme: "dark" }} />
```

### ✅ Memoized object

```jsx
const config = useMemo(() => ({ theme: "dark" }), []);
<Component config={config} />;
```

✅ Prevents shallow comparison failures

***

## ✅ 5. Split Components (Very Effective)

### ❌ One big component

```jsx
function Dashboard({ user }) {
  return (
    <>
      <Header user={user} />
      <Chart data={user.data} />
    </>
  );
}
```

### ✅ Smaller focused components

```jsx
const Header = React.memo(({ user }) => <h1>{user.name}</h1>);
const Chart = ({ data }) => { /* heavy */ };
```

✅ Limits re-render scope  
✅ Easier to optimize

***

## ✅ 6. Avoid Inline Objects, Arrays, and Functions in JSX

### ❌

```jsx
<List items={[1, 2, 3]} />
```

### ✅

```jsx
const items = useMemo(() => [1, 2, 3], []);
<List items={items} />
```

***

## ✅ 7. Context: Split It (Common Source of Over‑Renders)

### ❌ One large context

```jsx
<AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, theme, settings }}>
```

### ✅ Split contexts

```jsx
<UserContext />
<ThemeContext />
```

✅ Only consumers of changed data re-render

***

## ✅ 8. Select Only What You Need (Redux / Zustand / Context)

### ❌

```jsx
useSelector(state => state); // ❌ re-renders on any change
```

### ✅

```jsx
useSelector(state => state.user.name);
```

✅ Minimizes updates

***

## ✅ 9. Use Keys Correctly (Lists!)

### ❌ Index as key

```jsx
items.map((item, i) => <Row key={i} />)
```

### ✅ Stable key

```jsx
items.map(item => <Row key={item.id} />)
```

✅ Prevents unnecessary remounts

***

## ✅ 10. Don’t Optimize Blindly — Measure First

### ✅ Use React Profiler

*   React DevTools → Profiler
*   Identify *actual* bottlenecks

> **Most apps don’t need heavy optimization**

***

## ✅ Correct Optimization Priority (IMPORTANT)

1.  ✅ Localize state
2.  ✅ Split components
3.  ✅ Fix props stability
4.  ✅ Add `React.memo`
5.  ✅ Add `useCallback` / `useMemo`
6.  ✅ Measure again

***

## ✅ Common Mistakes to Avoid

❌ Memoizing everything  
❌ Using `useCallback` everywhere  
❌ Passing new objects/functions constantly  
❌ Blaming React instead of component design  
❌ Optimizing without profiling

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready Summary (MEMORIZE)

> **Unnecessary re‑renders are avoided by localizing state, splitting components, stabilizing props using useCallback and useMemo, and selectively applying React.memo based on profiling. Optimization should always be data‑driven, not premature.**

***

## ✅ TL;DR Cheat Sheet

✅ Local state first  
✅ Split components  
✅ Memoize only when needed  
✅ Stabilize props  
✅ Optimize after profiling

